<subsection xml:id="subsec-determining-the-linear-scale-factor-of-similar-figures" >
    <title>Determining The Linear Scale Factor of Similar Figures</title>

    <activity>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in pairs</alert>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Draw triangle <m>ABC</m> with the following side lengths as shown in the figure below (not drawn to scale):
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>AB = 9</m> cm, <m>AC = 6</m>cm, and <m>BC = 4</m>cm.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="triagle-i">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                       % Define triangle vertices
                    \coordinate (A) at (1,3);
                    \coordinate (B) at (5,0);
                    \coordinate (C) at (0,0);

                    % Draw the triangle without fill
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;

                    % Label vertices
                    \node at (1,3.2) {C};  % Adjust y slightly to position label above A
                    \node at (-0.1,-0.1) {A};  % Slightly shift left and down
                    \node at (5.2,-0.1) {B};  % Slightly shift right and down

                    % Label sides
                    \node at (2.5,-0.3) {7 cm};  % BC
                    \node at (3.4,1.7) {5 cm};   % AB
                    \node at (0,1.5) {6 cm};   % AC
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
        </task>
       
        
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Draw another triangle <m>PQR</m> with the following side lengths as shown in the figure below (not drawn to scale):
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>PQ = 27</m> cm, <m>PR = 18</m>cm, and <m>QR = 12</m>cm.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image label="triagle-ii">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                              % Define triangle vertices
                                \coordinate (R) at (0,0);
                                \coordinate (Q) at (5,0);
                                \coordinate (P) at (1,3);

                                % Draw the triangle (without fill)
                                \draw[thick] (R) -- (Q) -- (P) -- cycle;

                                % Label vertices close to the vertices
                                 \node at (1,3.2) {R};  % Adjust y slightly to position label above A
                                \node at (-0.1,-0.1) {P};  % Slightly shift left and down
                                \node at (5.2,-0.1) {Q};  % Slightly shift right and down

                                % Label sides
                                \node at (2.5,-0.3) {21 cm};
                                \node at (3.4,1.7) { 15 cm};
                                \node at (-0.1,1.5) { 18 cm};
                                   \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
        </task>
       
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the ratio of corresponding sides:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               <m>QR</m> to <m>BC</m> = <m>(QR/BC)</m>. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                              <m>PQ</m> to <m>AB</m> = <m>(PQ/AB)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               <m>PR</m> to <m>AC</m> = <m>(PR/AC)</m>. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What do you notice about the ratios of corresponding sides above?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>

        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What is the relationship between triangle <m>ABC</m> and triangle <m>PQR</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Discuss your findings and share your conclusions with the class.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>

    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway }</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        Linear scale factor is given by the ratio;
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Linear Scale Factor} = \frac{\textbf{Length of Side of an image }} {\textbf{Length of Corresponding Side of the object }}</m>
    </p>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                The two triangles <m>PQR</m> and <m>ABC</m> are similar. 
            </p>

            <sidebyside>
                <image>
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image label="similar-triagle1">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Triangle ABC (Blue fill)
                        \fill[blue!30] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (2,3.5) -- cycle;  % Light blue fill
                        \draw[thick, blue] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (2,3.5) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Labels for triangle ABC
                        \node[left] at (0,0) {A};
                        \node[right] at (5,0) {B};
                        \node[above] at (2,3.5) {C};
                        \node[below] at (2.5,0) {6 cm};
                        \node[left] at (1,2) {9 cm};
                        \node[right] at (3.5,2) {x};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                    
                </image>

                <image>
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Triangle ABC (Blue fill)
                        \fill[blue!30] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (2,3.5) -- cycle;  % Light blue fill
                        \draw[thick, blue] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (2,3.5) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Labels for triangle ABC
                        \node[left] at (0,0) {P};
                        \node[right] at (5,0) {Q};
                        \node[above] at (2,3.5) {R};
                        \node[below] at (2.5,0) {y cm};
                        \node[left] at (1,2) {12 cm};
                        \node[right] at (3.5,2) {14 cm};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                    
                </image>
            </sidebyside>

            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                  (i)  Determine the linear scale factor.
                </p>

                <p>
                   (ii) Calculate the lengths marked with letters <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                (i) Linear scale factor =<m>\frac{AC}{PR}=\frac{9}{12}=\frac{3}{4}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
              (ii)  <m>AB</m> corresponds to <m>PQ</m>, <m>BC</m> corresponds to <m>QR</m>, and <m>AC</m> corresponds to <m>PR</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Therefore,} \amp \frac{AB}{PQ}= \frac{AC}{PR}= \frac {BC}{QR} </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{6\, cm}{y}= \frac{9\, cm}{12\, cm}= \frac {x}{14\, cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \frac{6\, cm}{y}=\amp \frac{9\, cm}{12\, cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> y \times 9\, cm= \amp 6\, cm \times 12\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow> y= \amp \frac{72\, cm^2}{9\, cm}  </mrow>
                    <mrow> y =\amp 8\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Therefore PQ}= \amp 8 cm</mrow>
                     <mrow> \frac{9\, cm}{12\, cm}=\amp \frac{x}{14\, cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> x \times 12\, cm= \amp 9\, cm \times 14\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow> x= \amp \frac{126\, cm^2}{12\, cm}  </mrow>
                    <mrow> x =\amp 10.5\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Therefore BC}= \amp 10.5\, cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    
